A '''constitutional referendum''' was held in the [[Batavian Republic]] in 1798. After [[Batavian Republic constitutional referendum, 1797|a previous referendum in 1797]] resulted in a coup d'état, a new constitution was written. On 23 April 1798, a referendum was held about the new constitution. Only opponents of the federalists were allowed to vote.
After the referendum, a new coup d'état was done by the Unitarians, and the constitution became effective in July 1798. The French, who had a big influence in the Batavian Republic, were not satisfied with the 1798 constitution, so a new constitution was written, for which a [[Batavian Republic constitutional referendum, 1801|referendum in 1801]] was organized.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europa-nu.nl/id/vh8lnhrp8wt9/uitvoerend_bewind_1798_1801|title=Uitvoerend Bewind (1798-1801)|publisher=Europees parlement, Bureau Nederland en parlementair Documentatie Centrum UL}}</ref>
